Place a #large pan{} over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Season the @Irish Beef Rump{250%grams} with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Once the oil is hot fry the beef until browned, ~{1-2%mins} on each side for medium-rare.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat and its packaging.

Cook for another ~{1-2%mins} on each side if you want your beef medium.

Cook for ~{1-2%mins} extra on each side if you'd like it more well done.

Once cooked, transfer to a #cutting board{}, cover and allow to rest.

> IMPORTANT: Meat is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

Once the beef has rested for ~{1-2%mins}, slice into thin strips.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}.

Trim the @carrot{1}, then coarsely grate (no need to peel).

Trim the @Pak Choi{1}, then separate the leaves. Halve each leaf lengthways.

Thinly slice the @chilli{1} widthways at an angle.

Peel and grate the @ginger{1}. Use a #teaspoon{} to easily scrape away the peel.

Place a #large pot{} over medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil if required.

Once hot fry the onion, carrot and ginger until softened, stirring occasionally,
~{4-5%mins}.

Add the @Thai Style Spice Mix{1%sachet} and fry for ~{1%min} more.

Add 500ml @water{to taste} (double for 4p), @Worcester Sauce{1%sachet} and
@Beef Stock{1%sachet} to the pot then bring to the boil.

Roughly tear the @Basil{10%grams} leaves.

Carefully separate the @Udon Noodles{300%grams} and add to the broth with the sliced
chilli (use less if you don't like spice), sliced beef, pak choi and torn basil.

Cover and simmer for ~{4-6%mins}.

Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Divide the fragrant pho style beef soup between #bowls{}.

Serve hot.